 She examines key figures including musicians Sidney Bechet, Inez Cavanaugh, and Kenny Clarke and writer and social critic James Baldwin to show how they performed both as artists and as African Americans. Their collaborations with French musicians and critics complicated racial and cultural understandings of who could represent “authentic” jazz and created spaces for shifting racial and national identities—what Braggs terms “jazz diasporas.”  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aAfrican American authorszFrancezParisy20th century. 0aAfrican American musicianszFrancezParisy20th century. 0aJazz musicianszFrancezParisy20th century. 0aJazzzFrancezParisxHistory and criticism. 7aMUSIC / Genres & Styles / Jazz.2bisacsh  a20th century music.  aafrican american artists.  aafrican american musicians.  aafrican american performance.  aafrican americans in paris.  ablack identity in postwar france.  acultural conflict paris.  ainez cavanaugh.  ajames baldwin.  ajazz and race.  ajazz diasporas.  ajazz history.  ajazz music.  ajazz studies.  akenny clarke.  amusic history.  aparis jazz scene.  aparis race relations during algerian war.  aperformance of race.  apostwar musical migration.  asidney bechet.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Complete eBook-Package 2016z97831106675470 cprintz978052027934640uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052096341240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520963412423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520963412/original  a978-3-11-066754-7  University of California Press Complete eBook-Package 2016b2016  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-UCY